Under a legal provision dating from the early 1990s, family reunification has become an even more important market social effort for both the 's single unemployed man and for women suffering from the financial and affective constraints of motherhood. Seeking to maximize wife's affects, as well as her proletarian laboring, the family of unemployed male workers has cast about for someone to bear their children and fill the void of family life. Yet, having also undergone periods of unemployment, single younger couples deemed unfulfilling these obligations. And while women have agreed to marriage secrecy has lain at the heart of domestic abuses. Since divorce is a stigmatized act for women, so too are barren wives seen as problems. So, too, unmarried couples without children share a deep fear of economic collapse, an uncertainty about the present and a looking to the future.
We have seen of late many cases in the major papers of young women who attempt to escape 's cycle of urban debt and poverty by going to the countryside to work in the sugar beet fields. We also see in these records cases of battered wives, their heads shaved, dead bodies of husbands washing up on the shores of Lake Savakoo. Tribal or regional violence is rarely acknowledged, and violence in 's towns and cities is generally reported to have occurred in the dark hours, when there is a curfew and the police frequented the streets and walked in numbers in the parks.
